etymologies: late 17th century; earliest use found in Obadiah Walker (1616–1699), college head and author. From re- + stamp

definitions: To stamp a new pattern or mark on (a surface, object, etc.).
To reimpress (a mark, image, etc.) on an object, surface, etc. Chiefly in figurative, especially spiritual, contexts; (now also figurative) to reassert or reaffirm (one's authority).
